subSubSection.paragraph:
Pronotum (
Fig. 4
) slightly wider than head and narrower than the mesonotum (except the pronotal collar). Ambient fissure with black band extending to middle of pronotum and to lateral margins of pronotal collar. Paranota wide (reaching the eyes) and convex, visible in dorsal view. Mesonotum (
Fig. 4
) with submedian sigillae stained in black and lateral sigillae stained in black anteriorly, black band extending laterally reaching the scutellum. Scutal depression stained in black. Apex of posterior projections of scutellum slightly pointed. Epimeral lobel reaching the anteromedian margin of operculum, directed posteriorly. Anepimeron 2 shorter than epimeral lobe, apex directed laterally. Basisternum 3 (
Fig. 5
) with well-developed protuberances relative to median insertion, protuberances apices spaced. Posterior margin of basisternum 3 straight. Operculum (
Fig. 6
) triangular, apex closing the tympanal cavity, lateral margin convex, posterior margin curved, meracanthus does not reaches the posterior opercular margin. Internal angles of operculum wide, the apex obtuse and widely separated, gutter present on entire margin of operculum. Profemora armed with three spines, primary round at apex and leaning forward, secondary sharp and straight, and apical straight and shorter than others. Three segmented tarsi. Wings hyaline. Fore wings with median vein divergent to cubitus anterior vein, basal cell entirely opaque, apical cell 2 shorter than 1 and 3, medial crossvein oblique. Hind wings with radius vein straight.

Abdomen conical, the length equivalent to combined length of head and thorax in dorsal view. Timbal cover (Fig. 3) tumid, rounded apex reaching the metascutellar plate, the medial margin straight completely covering timbals. Tergite 1 visible. Sternite I not visible in ventral view. Posterior margin of sternite II concave. Median projection of sternite II long, reaching the posterior limit of metacoxae. Sternite VII (
Fig. 7
) sub-rectangular, lateral margin straight. Sternite VIII in ogive-shaped with spines in posterior margin.

Pygofer (
Fig. 8
) with rounded distal shoulder. Basal lobe of pygofer short, not reaching the lateral uncus lobes and not delimited with the lateral margin of pygofer. Uncus (
Fig. 101
) with spines and lateral margins convex. Median uncus lobe triangular with median suture and narrow lateral margins in ventral view. Lateral uncus lobes wide and obtuse, expanded laterally in ventral view, forming a horse shoe-shaped structure in posterior view. Protuberance of basal plate distant from apex of basal lobe. Basal curve of aedeagus short, near to lateral lobes. Theca (
Figs. 9, 10
) expanded laterally to vesica, left part extending beyond the apex forming a short horn relative to size of theca. Vesica originates in fissure at theca, extruded in round shape, with gonopore near apex.

Female.
Same somatic characteristics of male except operculum (
Fig. 11
) smaller, posterior margin sinuous, lateral margin convex, meracanthus over internal angle. Sternite VII (
Fig. 12
) longer, sub-rectangular, posterior margin sinuous with obtuse middle groove. Ovipositor sheath extending same distance as tip of dorsal beak. Ovipositor (
Fig.13
) with eight teeth.
